{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"34ab5662-e9dd-4a64-b798-b6c9a258bf7c","content":"\n\nIn .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle events API** in `MauiProgram.cs` (or your app builder configuration):\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on Android pause */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* runs on Android stop */ }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on iOS background */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\nYou'll need:\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n```\n\nThis maps directly to the native events without requiring custom platform code. Each handler receives the native object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS), so you can call platform APIs if needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ee49bbb1-f796-4e48-8d20-0993e706d08c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's `OnPause`/`OnStop` and iOS's `DidEnterBackground`. This is a general knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":291},"id":"89f5b5f7-33be-49fd-83d3-4a49a158ae6f","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:45:27.758Z","parentId":"d3797bf8-2479-4118-8ee9-515dc14c610e"}
